= section "Structure of the Noun" do
  %p Očets is a predominantly agglutinating language with a high morpheme-to-word ratio. That being said, the exact lines between morphemes can at times be hard to identify due to various forms of inter-morpheme interactions.
  %p The typical native Očets root consists of one or two syllables, the most common forms being CV, CVC, CVCC, CVC(C)V, or CVCVC (where “C” represents a consonant and “V” a vowel or diphthong). Derived stems can be longer and have different syllable structures. More recent loans can have almost any shape. In roots of CVCVC structure, the second “V” may drop in certain inflections if it is a short or reduced vowel, though never if it is a long vowel. There are no restrictions on the distribution of long and short vowels, except in CV-type roots, which must have a long vowel or diphthong. Some example roots:
  %ul
    %li
      CV
      %ul
        %li <i>*šyy</i> “sun”
        %li <i>*xee</i> “night”
        %li <i>*čaa</i> “salt”
        %li <i>*tai</i> “frost”
        %li <i>*mei</i> “fruit”
    %li
      CVC
      %ul
        %li <i>*kuor</i> “village”
        %li <i>*sič</i> “snow”
        %li <i>*nas</i> “eye”
        %li <i>*den</i> “lake”
        %li <i>*kyys</i> “baby”
    %li
      CVCC
      %ul
        %li <i>*bulg</i> “uneasiness”
        %li <i>*seeŋk</i> “coin”
        %li <i>*šips</i> “hill”
        %li <i>*qants</i> “ant”
        %li <i>*iast</i> “stomach”
    %li
      CVC(C)V
      %ul
        %li <i>*kalča</i> “trash”
        %li <i>*meme</i> “mother”
        %li <i>*torma</i> “prison”
        %li <i>*hunne</i> “wolf”
        %li <i>*heždi</i> “sable”
    %li
      CVCVC
      %ul
        %li <i>*heemis</i> “raspberry”
        %li <i>*daǧən</i> “edible plant, vegetable”
        %li <i>*texəl</i> “otter”
        %li <i>*haatər</i> “front door”
        %li <i>*čieǧəl</i> “sled”
    %li
      Other Native (&gt;300 years old)
      %ul
        %li <i>*plis</i> “splash”
        %li <i>*hurgaan</i> “powerful wind storm”
        %li <i>*škaan</i> “hair of the head”
    %li
      Other Foreign (&lt; ~300 years old)
      %ul
        %li <i>*otobus</i> “bus”
        %li <i>*kompiutər</i> “computer”
        %li <i>*park</i> “park”
        %li <i>*raadio</i> “radio”
        %li <i>*skoola</i> “school”
  %p Notice that final clusters appear in a number of inherited roots, but initial clusters are very rare, and appear to always originate from onomatopoeia (as with <i>*plis</i>) or irregular reduction of compounds (as with <i>*škaan</i>, from Proto-Ob-Yeniseian *k<sup>y</sup>i-qā-n’ (head-hair-#{abbrev 'coll'}).
  %p Roots of the form CVCəC, with a reduced vowel, can usually also be interpreted as CVCC roots which end in an illegal final cluster. In this analysis, the root for “otter” is <i>*texl</i>, but in isolation it becomes <i>texəl</i> because /xl/ is not permitted as a final cluster. This view works well when a suffix beginning with a vowel is added (<i>texle</i> “otter-#{abbrev 'obj'}”), but can be problematic when a suffix beginning with a consonant is added (<i>texəlze</i> “otter-#{abbrev 'gen'}”—why not **texləze?).
  %p The noun root must be distinguished from the noun stem, which can have a very different overall structure and can easily be four, five, or more syllables in length. A noun stem consists of a root plus any derivational affixes; this is the base to which grammatical affixes are added. For so-called “simple” nouns, including many of the ones listed above, the root and stem are identical.
  %p All Očets nouns inherently belong to one of two noun classes. One, which for sake of brevity will be called “animate”, includes all nouns referring to people, terms for “useful” animals (generally meaning domesticated or huntable species), edible plants, and certain body parts (particularly those that do work, such as hands or feet, or those responsible with sense perception, such as the eyes, tongue, or ears). Self-powered vehicles such as cars, ships containing a motor, and airplanes are included as well, perhaps by analogy with the beasts of burden. The other classs, here referred to as “inanimate”, includes all other nouns. These two classes have different declensions and behave slightly differently syntactically. There is also a third specialized quantifier declension that is not inherent, but which other nouns can transfer into in certain circumstances. This will be discussed later.
  %table
    %tr
      %th Animate
      %th Inanimate
    %tr
      %td <i>*baba</i> — “father”
      %td <i>*ǧuu</i> — “house”
    %tr
      %td <i>*niit</i> — “sister”
      %td <i>*xil</i> — “sky”
    %tr
      %td <i>*stas</i> — “teacher”
      %td <i>*šyy</i> — “sun”
    %tr
      %td <i>*čib</i> — “dog”
      %td <i>*hok</i> — “tree”
    %tr
      %td <i>*hyyn</i> — “cow”
      %td <i>*hoǧ</i> — “grass”
    %tr
      %td <i>*iai</i> — “deer”
      %td <i>*kaa</i> — “mountain”
    %tr
      %td <i>*sor</i> — “fish”
      %td <i>*kwor</i> — “water”
    %tr
      %td <i>*šyynd</i> — “wheat”
      %td <i>*wino</i> — “wine”
    %tr
      %td <i>*holma</i> — “apple”
      %td <i>*hiot</i> — “mouse”
    %tr
      %td <i>*kaartok</i> — “potato”
      %td <i>*kwoi</i> — “bear”
    %tr
      %td <i>*nas</i> — “eye”
      %td <i>*iast</i> — “stomach”
    %tr
      %td <i>*ǧal</i> — “hand”
      %td <i>*čii</i> — “head”
    %tr
      %td <i>*hele</i> — “nose”
      %td <i>*dax</i> — “land”
    %tr
      %td <i>*wooz</i> — “car”
      %td <i>*laad</i> — “city”
    %tr
      %td <i>*samoled</i> — “airplane”
      %td <i>*šuud</i> — “happiness”
  %p Očets nouns inflect for case, number, definiteness, and possessor. There are also several miscellaneous affixes.
  %p All nouns are also inherently front-vowel roots, back-vowel roots, or “epicene” roots, as determined by the final vowel of the root (or next-to-last if the last is a schwa). Front-vowel roots only take affixes with front vowels, while back-vowel roots only take affixes with back vowels. Epicene nouns can go either way according to some somewhat complex rules. This is complicated, however, by the fact that certain affixes are harmony-neutral and therefore invariable. These are subdivided further into two types: “weak” neutral vowels which simply ignore harmony rules, and “strong” neutral vowels which force all subsequent vowels to follow their own harmony pattern, ignoring whatever the noun root may normally call for. Compare, for instance, the following:
  = example_sentence :ochets => "котыынемакаи",
                     :translit => "kotyynemakai",
                     :breakdown => "ko-tyy-n-em-a-kai",
                     :underlying => "*ko{b}-tyy{b+}s-n-è{f}m-A{b}-kA{b}i",
                     :gloss => "#{abbrev '2sg'}-brother-#{abbrev 'pl'}-#{abbrev 'tra'}-#{abbrev 'ind'}-and",
                     :eng => "and [as] your brothers"
  = example_sentence :ochets => "котыынеечеи",
                     :translit => "kotyyneečei",
                     :breakdown => "ko-tyy-n-e-e-čei",
                     :underlying => "*ko{b}-tyy{b+}s-n-è{f+}-A{f}-kA{f}i",
                     :gloss => "#{abbrev '2sg'}-brother-#{abbrev 'pl'}-#{abbrev 'obj'}-#{abbrev 'ind'}-and",
                     :eng => "and [to] your brothers"
  %p The first word means “and your brothers” in the translative case, while the second means the same thing in the objective case. Both are back-vowel roots, as can be seen in the root vowel /ɨ:/. However, in both of these words, after the plural suffix is a case ending containing a neutral vowel /e/. In the first case, it is weak, so even though the suffix introduces a front vowel /e/, the plural possessive suffix afterwards still contains a back vowel—the case suffix had no effect on harmony at all, despite its own dissonance with the otherwise back-vowel-dominated word. Thus both the indirective suffix and clitic “and” show back-vowel harmony, according to the root <i>*tyys</i>.
  %p In the second example, however, this /e/ is strong, and therefore “resets” the harmony of the word for all morphemes after it; thus the indirective suffix and clitic “and” show front-vowel harmony, despite the root.
  %p Due to the complexity of both the harmony system and sandhi, a special notation will be used to indicate underlying forms alongside surface forms. Underlying forms will always be preceded by an asterisk, like so:
  = example_sentence :ochets => "тадаҕнее",
                     :translit => "tadaǧnee",
                     :breakdown => "ta-daǧn-e-e",
                     :underlying => "*tV-da{b+}ǧə{0}n-è{f+}-A{f}",
                     :gloss => "#{abbrev 'def'}-vegetable-#{abbrev 'obj'}-#{abbrev 'ind'}",
                     :eng => "[to] the plant"
  %p The first line above represents native script, the second transliteration, the third a simplified breakdown, the fourth a breakdown of the underlying form, and the fifth a gloss.
  %p Hyphens indicate morpheme boundaries. Superscripts indicate whether a vowel is f(ront), b(ack), or 0 (suppressed). A plus sign after the superscript means this is a harmony-determining vowel, that is, that all vowels following it must match its harmony pattern. In the above example, the back /f/ of the root <i>*daǧən</i> “vegetable” triggers back harmony, but this is then suppressed in favor of front vowel harmony by the objective suffix *-e-, which consists of a strong neutral vowel. Therefore, all affixes following this will have front vowels. If there were an affix between the root and the accusative suffix, it would have back vowel harmony, since it precedes the syllable inducing front vowels.
  %p When a majuscule vowel appears, this represents a vowel whose quality determined by harmony. “A” represents /e ~ a/, “O” /ø ~ o/, “U” /y ~ u/, and “I” /i ~ ɨ/. An affix *-A- will therefore appear as /a/ on the surface if back vowel harmony is required, or as /e/ if front vowel harmony is needed. The vowels “è” and “ì”, featuring a grave accent, will not trigger palatalization of the previous consonant, while regular “e” and “i” will. A plain “V” with no other markings represents a vowel whose qualities are determined by some other rule; in this case, the definite prefix *tV- tends to match the first vowel of the following syllable.
  %p Note that è can occur word-internally as well; in such cases, it acts as though it were a back vowel for all intents and purposes. For instance, <i>*dèn</i> “people”, despite containing a front vowel, always takes back vowel endings, as in the genitive plural <i>dènda</i>.
  %p If all slots are indicated, the Očets noun may be diagrammed as follows. Number markers may appear in several different locations, depending on what other affixes are present.
  %table.slottable
    %tr
      %th +2
      %th +1
      %th 0
      %th -1
      %th -2
      %th -3
      %th -4
      %th -5
    %tr
      %td Prenominal Prefix
      %td
        Definite Article
        %br
        or
        %br
        Possessive Prefix
      %td Stem
      %td Number Marker (Type 1)
      %td Case Ending
      %td Number Marker (Type 2)
      %td
        Relative Suffix
        %br
        or
        %br
        Indirective Suffix
      %td Predicative Suffix
  %p The following sections will discuss these different types of affixes one by one. Unfortunately, due to the significant interaction between affixes, it is impossible to completely compartmentalize them. Each of the following sections will therefore build upon the previous sections. The following section on cases will deal with them only in the singular; when plural suffixes are discussed, cases will be brought up again insofar as they are related to plural suffixes; and so on.

= section "Cases" do
  %p Both animate and inanimate nouns inflect for eight cases: nominative (#{abbrev 'nom'}), objective (#{abbrev 'obj'}), genitive (#{abbrev 'gen'}), instrumental (#{abbrev 'ins'}), locative (#{abbrev 'loc'}), lative (#{abbrev 'lat'}), translative (#{abbrev 'tra'}), and ablative (#{abbrev 'abl'}). These are all marked by suffixes appearing after the noun root.

  = section "Nominative Case" do
    %p The nominative case is primarily used to mark the subject of most verbs (and sometimes the direct object), as well as the object of most prepositions and appositive nouns modifying other nouns. It is the simplest case morphologically, consisting of no affix to the noun stem for both animate and inanimate nouns.
    = render 'noun_endings', :animate => "-Ø", :inanimate => "-Ø"
    %p The nominative singular indefinite of most nouns is thus formed simply with the bare stem. However, if the stem begins with a vowel, an epenthetic /h/ is added to the beginning of the word. If the noun is epicene and its root contains an indeterminate vowel (i.e., a schwa and no other vowel to determine harmony), such as *-šəǧ- “light” or *-pəs- “manner”, this vowel will default to #{underlying "/e/{f+}"} if the consonant immediately following is /ʃ ʒ tʃ dʒ/, or #{underlying "/a/{b+}"} otherwise. If the stem ends in an illegal word-final cluster, an epenthetic schwa may be inserted between the last two consonants: *-sent- “heart” → <i>sent</i>, but *-texl- “otter” → <i>texəl</i>.
    %p If the noun contains a velar consonant which is followed by a stressed long or short /o u/ and is not in a consonant cluster, it will usually become labialized. This does not apply to more recent loans. This process is quite regular and predictable: velars become labialized before such stressed vowels, and lose the labialization when the vowel loses its stress. Note that /g/ becomes /kʷ/ when labialized. Compare: *kosa ‘cat’ → #{t "коса", "kosá"} “a cat”, #{t "токвосаа", "tokwósaa"} “the cat”.
    %p The following table demonstrates the nominative singular of example roots. <i>*meme</i> “mother”, <i>*nas</i> “eye”, <i>*čib</i> “dog”, <i>*ǧəl</i> “hand”, and <i>*sent</i> “heart” are all animate, while <i>*xee</i> “night”, <i>*huun</i> “morning”, <i>*iš</i> “meat”, <i>*čieǧl</i> “sled”, and <i>*laad</i> “city” are inanimate.
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*meme", :eng => "mother", :ochets => "меме", :translit => "meme", :breakdown => "meme-Ø", :underlying => "me{f}me{f+}-Ø" },
                { :stem => "*nas", :eng => "eye", :ochets => "нас", :translit => "nas", :breakdown => "nas-Ø", :underlying => "na{b+}s-Ø" },
                { :stem => "*čib", :eng => "dog", :ochets => "чиб", :translit => "čib", :breakdown => "čib-Ø", :underlying => "či{f+}b-Ø" },
                { :stem => "*ǧəl", :eng => "hand", :ochets => "ҕал", :translit => "ǧal", :breakdown => "ǧal-Ø", :underlying => "ǧə{b+}l-Ø" },
                { :stem => "*sent", :eng => "heart", :ochets => "сент", :translit => "sent", :breakdown => "sent-Ø", :underlying => "se{f+}nt-Ø" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Animate", :forms => forms
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*xee", :eng => "night", :ochets => "хее", :translit => "xee", :breakdown => "xee-Ø", :underlying => "xee{f+}-Ø" },
                { :stem => "*huun", :eng => "morning", :ochets => "һуун", :translit => "huun", :breakdown => "huun-Ø", :underlying => "huu{b+}n-Ø" },
                { :stem => "*iš", :eng => "meat", :ochets => "һиш", :translit => "hiš", :breakdown => "hiš-Ø", :underlying => "i{f+}š-Ø" },
                { :stem => "*čieǧl", :eng => "sled", :ochets => "чиеҕәл", :translit => "čieǧəl", :breakdown => "čieǧəl-Ø", :underlying => "čie{f+}ǧl-Ø" },
                { :stem => "*laad", :eng => "city", :ochets => "лаад", :translit => "laad", :breakdown => "laad-Ø", :underlying => "laa{b+}d-Ø" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Inanimate", :forms => forms

  = section "Objective Case" do
    %p The objective case is most often used to mark the direct object of a verb, though it also can mark the indirect object in certain circumstances. It is marked for animate nouns with the non-palatalizing strong neutral vowel #{underlying "*-è{f+}-"}, and for inanimate nouns with either #{underlying "*-è{f+}-"} or #{underlying "*-s-"}.
    = render 'noun_endings', :animate => "-è{f+}", :inanimate => "-è{f+}, -s"
    %p Animate nouns will always use #{underlying "*-è{f+}-"}, even if the stem itself contains only back vowels. If the stem ends in a vowel, however, this accusative marker gains an epenthetic /l/ to prevent hiatus (after /i/, /y/, or /ɨ/), simply lengthens the preceding vowel (after /e/, /ø/, or /a/), or disappears entirely (after /o/ and /u/, or any long vowel).
    %p However, if the stem is polysyllabic, ends in a vowel that typically lengthens (i.e., /e ø a/), and contains a long vowel in the syllable immediately beforehand, that earlier vowel will shorten: #{t "һотәскоола", "hotəskoola"} “students in a school (#{abbrev 'nom'})” → #{t "һотәсколаа", "hotəskolaa"}.
    %p All indeterminate vowels in epicene or front-vowel roots become /e/; indeterminate vowels only remain as /a/ if the root contains another fixed back vowel.
    %p Inanimate nouns simply take #{underlying "*-s-"} regularly if the root ends in a vowel, or #{underlying "*-è{f+}-"} if it ends in a consonant.
    %p If the syllable immediately before the suffix #{underlying "-è{f+}-"} contains short /a/, it will often mutate to -è-, although it still patterns as a back vowel.
    %p In CVCVC roots, the second vowel will drop if it is short.
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*meme", :eng => "mother", :ochets => "мемее", :translit => "memee", :breakdown => "meme-e", :underlying => "me{f}me{f+}-è{f+}" },
                { :stem => "*nas", :eng => "eye", :ochets => "несе", :translit => "nese", :breakdown => "nes-e", :underlying => "na{b+}s-è{f+}" },
                { :stem => "*čib", :eng => "dog", :ochets => "чибе", :translit => "čibe", :breakdown => "čib-e", :underlying => "či{f+}b-è{f+}" },
                { :stem => "*ǧəl", :eng => "hand", :ochets => "ҕеле", :translit => "ǧele", :breakdown => "ǧel-e", :underlying => "ǧə{f}l-è{f+}" },
                { :stem => "*sent", :eng => "heart", :ochets => "сенте", :translit => "sente", :breakdown => "sent-e", :underlying => "se{f+}nt-è{f+}" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Animate", :forms => forms
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*xee", :eng => "night", :ochets => "хеес", :translit => "xees", :breakdown => "xee-s", :underlying => "xee{f+}-s" },
                { :stem => "*huun", :eng => "morning", :ochets => "һууне", :translit => "huune", :breakdown => "huun-e", :underlying => "huu{b+}n-è{f+}" },
                { :stem => "*iš", :eng => "meat", :ochets => "һише", :translit => "hiše", :breakdown => "hiš-e", :underlying => "i{f+}š-è{f+}" },
                { :stem => "*čieǧl", :eng => "sled", :ochets => "чиеҕле", :translit => "čieǧle", :breakdown => "čieǧl-e", :underlying => "čie{f+}ǧl-è{f+}" },
                { :stem => "*laad", :eng => "city", :ochets => "лааде", :translit => "laade", :breakdown => "laad-e", :underlying => "laa{b+}d-è{f+}" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Inanimate", :forms => forms

  = section "Genitive Case" do
    %p The genitive case marks the possessor of another noun. It is formed by the suffix #{underlying "*-dA-"} for animate nouns and #{underlying "*-dI-"} for inanimate nouns (although there are a few exceptions, noted below). The vowel in this suffix is marked for harmony, and so becomes /e/ (animate) or /i/ (inanimate) if the noun triggers front harmony or /a/ (animate) or /ɨ/ (inanimate) if it triggers back harmony. However, if the vowel becomes /i/ or /e/, this in turn palatalizes the /d/ to /z/: #{underlying "*-dA{f}"}/#{underlying "*-dI{f}"} → *-de/*-di → -ze/-zi.
    = render 'noun_endings', :animate => "-dA", :animate_comments => "(-da, -ze, -d, -z, -əd, -əz)", :inanimate => "-dI", :inanimate_comments => "(-dy, -zi, -d, -z, -əd, -əz)"
    %p If the root ends in a single consonant, the genitive suffix is added directly after the root, and the C-d or C-z cluster formed may undergo sandhi as described in the table in section 2.5.3. If the root ends in two consonants, however, any cluster would be illegal, so an epenthetic /ə/ is inserted between the root and the genitive suffix. If the noun root is monosyllabic and the genitive is added after a vowel (i.e., the root ends in a vowel, or the root ends in a cluster such that an epenthetic vowel is inserted before the genitive), the vowel of the genitive suffix drops entirely, though any palatalization it may have caused beforehand remains: #{underlying "*V-dA{f}"}/#{underlying "*V-dI{f}"} → *V-de/*V-di → *V-ze/*V-zi → V-z.
    %p In CVCVC roots, no vowel is dropped. Indeterminate vowels revert to whatever they were in the nominative case.
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*meme", :eng => "mother", :ochets => "мемези", :translit => "memezi", :breakdown => "meme-zi", :underlying => "me{f}me{f+}-dI{f}" },
                { :stem => "*nas", :eng => "eye", :ochets => "назда", :translit => "nazda", :breakdown => "naz-da", :underlying => "na{b+}s-dA{b}" },
                { :stem => "*čib", :eng => "dog", :ochets => "чибзе", :translit => "čibze", :breakdown => "čib-ze", :underlying => "či{f+}b-dA{f}" },
                { :stem => "*ǧəl", :eng => "hand", :ochets => "ҕалда", :translit => "ǧalda", :breakdown => "ǧal-da", :underlying => "ǧə{b}l-dA{b}" },
                { :stem => "*sent", :eng => "heart", :ochets => "сентәз", :translit => "sentəz", :breakdown => "sent-əz", :underlying => "se{f+}nt-dA{f→0}" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Animate", :forms => forms
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*xee", :eng => "night", :ochets => "хеез", :translit => "xeez", :breakdown => "xee-z", :underlying => "xee{f+}-dI{f→0}" },
                { :stem => "*huun", :eng => "morning", :ochets => "һуунды", :translit => "huundy", :breakdown => "huun-dy", :underlying => "huu{b+}n-dI{b}" },
                { :stem => "*iš", :eng => "meat", :ochets => "һиззи", :translit => "hizzi", :breakdown => "hiz-zi", :underlying => "i{f+}š-dI{f}" },
                { :stem => "*čieǧl", :eng => "sled", :ochets => "чиеҕләз", :translit => "cieǧləz", :breakdown => "čieǧlə-z", :underlying => "čie{f+}ǧl-dI{f→0}" },
                { :stem => "*laad", :eng => "city", :ochets => "лаадды", :translit => "laaddy", :breakdown => "laad-dy", :underlying => "laa{b+}d-dI{b}" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Inanimate", :forms => forms
    %p The one exception to the general rule of genitive endings is that feminine kinship terms, which are all animate, always take the inanimate ending #{underlying "-dI"} rather than the animate #{underlying "-dA"}. Proto-Ob-Yeniseian is believed to have had a three-way gender contrast of masculine, feminine, and inanimate, with the masculine genitive marked by *-da and the feminine and inanimate genitive by *-di. In Proto-Ob, the masculine and feminine merged as the animate, but the feminine possessive retained its use for these few very common words.

  = section "Instrumental Case" do
    %p The instrumental case plays a number of roles; it can at various times serve as the subject, direct object, or indirect object of a verb. It also describes the means by which an action is performed. The instrumental is marked for both animate and inanimate nouns with the suffix #{underlying "*-Às-"}, that is, *-as- when back harmony is present, or *-ès- when front harmony is present. The second vowel in CVCVC roots drops if it is short. Indeterminate vowels tend to become /a/ in all cases.
    = render 'noun_endings', :animate => "-Às, -Àk", :animate_comments => "(-as, -es, -ak, -ek)", :inanimate => "-Às", :inanimate_comments => "(-as, -es)"
    %p If the root ends in a vowel, the same rules apply as in the accusative case: an epenthetic /l/ is added after /i y ɨ/, the root vowel is lengthened and the suffix vowel is lost after /a e ø/, and the suffix vowel is simply lost after /o u/ and long vowels. The same shortening rule applies as in the objective animate as well, except for inanimate nouns as well, so that the instrumental of #{t "скоола", "skoola"} “school” is #{t "сколаас", "skolaas"}.
    %p A very small set of nouns, all of which are animate, instead form the instrumental with #{underlying "*-Àk-"} rather than #{underlying "*-Às-"}. This derives from an older dative suffix that has long since lost productivity. The most basic kinship terms, for instance, use this form.
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*meme", :eng => "mother", :ochets => "мемеек", :translit => "memeek", :breakdown => "meme-ek", :underlying => "me{f}me{f+}-À{f}k" },
                { :stem => "*nas", :eng => "eye", :ochets => "насас", :translit => "nasas", :breakdown => "nas-as", :underlying => "na{b+}s-À{b}s" },
                { :stem => "*čib", :eng => "dog", :ochets => "чибес", :translit => "čibes", :breakdown => "čib-es", :underlying => "či{f+}b-À{f}s" },
                { :stem => "*ǧəl", :eng => "hand", :ochets => "ҕалас", :translit => "ǧalas", :breakdown => "ǧal-as", :underlying => "ǧə{b}l-À{b}s" },
                { :stem => "*sent", :eng => "heart", :ochets => "сентес", :translit => "sentes", :breakdown => "sent-es", :underlying => "se{f+}nt-À{f}s" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Animate", :forms => forms
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*xee", :eng => "night", :ochets => "хеес", :translit => "xees", :breakdown => "xee-s", :underlying => "xee{f+}-À{f→0}s" },
                { :stem => "*huun", :eng => "morning", :ochets => "һуунас", :translit => "huunas", :breakdown => "huun-as", :underlying => "huu{b+}n-À{b}s" },
                { :stem => "*iš", :eng => "meat", :ochets => "һишес", :translit => "hišes", :breakdown => "hiš-es", :underlying => "i{f+}š-À{f}s" },
                { :stem => "*čieǧl", :eng => "sled", :ochets => "чиеҕлес", :translit => "cieǧles", :breakdown => "čieǧl-es", :underlying => "čie{f+}ǧl-À{f}s" },
                { :stem => "*laad", :eng => "city", :ochets => "лаадас", :translit => "laadas", :breakdown => "laad-as", :underlying => "laa{b+}d-À{b}s" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Inanimate", :forms => forms

  = section "Locative Case" do
    %p The locative case marks the location where an action takes place, and for certain verbs may mark the subject or object. The basic suffix is #{underlying "*-Ìl-"} for both animate and inanimate nouns. However, stems that end in velar plosive or fricative consonants will always take -yl-, no matter the harmony: #{t "квоох", "kwoox"} “east (#{abbrev 'nom'})” → #{t "квоохыл", "kwooxyl"} “in the east”, #{t "һелх", "helx"} “door (#{abbrev 'nom'})” → #{t "һелхыл", "helxyl"} “at the door”.
    %p If the noun stem ends in a vowel, the locative suffix reduces to just -l-.
    = render 'noun_endings', :animate => "-Ìl, -yl", :animate_comments => "(-yl, -il, -l)", :inanimate => "-Ìl, -yl", :inanimate_comments => "(-yl, -il, -l)"
    %p CVCVC nouns lose their second vowel if it is short. Indeterminate vowels match the vowel of the nominative form.
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*meme", :eng => "mother", :ochets => "мемел", :translit => "memel", :breakdown => "meme-l", :underlying => "me{f}me{f+}-Ì{0}l" },
                { :stem => "*nas", :eng => "eye", :ochets => "насыл", :translit => "nasyl", :breakdown => "nas-yl", :underlying => "na{b+}s-Ì{b}l" },
                { :stem => "*čib", :eng => "dog", :ochets => "чибил", :translit => "čibil", :breakdown => "čib-il", :underlying => "či{f+}b-Ì{f}l" },
                { :stem => "*ǧəl", :eng => "hand", :ochets => "ҕалыл", :translit => "ǧalyl", :breakdown => "ǧal-yl", :underlying => "ǧə{b}l-Ì{b}l" },
                { :stem => "*sent", :eng => "heart", :ochets => "сентил", :translit => "sentil", :breakdown => "sent-il", :underlying => "se{f+}nt-Ì{f}l" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Animate", :forms => forms
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*xee", :eng => "night", :ochets => "хеел", :translit => "xeel", :breakdown => "xee-l", :underlying => "xee{f+}-Ì{0}l" },
                { :stem => "*huun", :eng => "morning", :ochets => "һууныл", :translit => "huunyl", :breakdown => "huun-yl", :underlying => "huu{b+}n-Ì{b}l" },
                { :stem => "*iš", :eng => "meat", :ochets => "һишил", :translit => "hišil", :breakdown => "hiš-il", :underlying => "i{f+}š-Ì{f}l" },
                { :stem => "*čieǧl", :eng => "sled", :ochets => "чиеҕлил", :translit => "cieǧlil", :breakdown => "čieǧl-il", :underlying => "čie{f+}ǧl-Ì{f}l" },
                { :stem => "*laad", :eng => "city", :ochets => "лаадыл", :translit => "laadyl", :breakdown => "laad-yl", :underlying => "laa{b+}d-Ì{b}l" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Inanimate", :forms => forms

  = section "Lative Case" do
    %p The lative case is primarily used to mark the destination of a verb of motion. Animate nouns take the suffix #{underlying "*-na{b+}-"}, while inanimate nouns take #{underlying "*-lA-"}. Animate nouns show no form of vowel harmony.
    = render 'noun_endings', :animate => "-na", :animate_comments => "(-na, -na, -ona)", :inanimate => "-lA", :inanimate_comments => "(-la, -le, -ola)"
    %p If the stem ends in a single consonant, it may undergo sandhi with the first consonant of the lative suffix. If it ends in a cluster, the lative suffix will become -ona (animate) or -ola (inanimate, regardless of harmony), with a strong back vowel; the one exception is when the cluster ends in /t/ or /d/, in which case the /t/ or /d/ will drop and normal suffixes are used: #{t "саалч", "saalč"} “sea (#{abbrev 'nom'})” → #{t "саалчола", "saalčola"} “to sea”, #{t "сент", "sent"} “heart (#{abbrev 'nom'})” → #{t "сенна", "senna"} “heart (#{abbrev 'lat'})”.
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*meme", :eng => "mother", :ochets => "мемена", :translit => "memena", :breakdown => "meme-na", :underlying => "me{f}me{f+}-na{b+}" },
                { :stem => "*nas", :eng => "eye", :ochets => "назна", :translit => "nazna", :breakdown => "naz-na", :underlying => "na{b+}s-na{b+}" },
                { :stem => "*čib", :eng => "dog", :ochets => "чимна", :translit => "čimna", :breakdown => "čim-na", :underlying => "či{f+}b-na{b+}" },
                { :stem => "*ǧəl", :eng => "hand", :ochets => "ҕална", :translit => "ǧalna", :breakdown => "ǧal-na", :underlying => "ǧə{b}l-na{b+}" },
                { :stem => "*sent", :eng => "heart", :ochets => "сенна", :translit => "senna", :breakdown => "sen-na", :underlying => "se{f+}nt-na{b+}" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Animate", :forms => forms
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*xee", :eng => "night", :ochets => "хееле", :translit => "xeele", :breakdown => "xee-le", :underlying => "xee{f+}-lA{f}" },
                { :stem => "*huun", :eng => "morning", :ochets => "һуулла", :translit => "huulla", :breakdown => "huul-la", :underlying => "huu{b+}n-lA{b}" },
                { :stem => "*iš", :eng => "meat", :ochets => "һишле", :translit => "hišle", :breakdown => "hiš-le", :underlying => "i{f+}š-lA{f}" },
                { :stem => "*čieǧl", :eng => "sled", :ochets => "чиеҕлола", :translit => "cieǧlola", :breakdown => "čieǧl-ola", :underlying => "čie{f+}ǧl-o{b+}la{b}" },
                { :stem => "*laad", :eng => "city", :ochets => "лаалла", :translit => "laalla", :breakdown => "laal-la", :underlying => "laa{b+}d-lA{b}" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Inanimate", :forms => forms

  = section "Translative Case" do
    %p The translative case indicates a change in state, or sometimes just simple static states. The suffix is #{underlying "*-èm-"} or #{underlying "*-m-"} for animate nouns and #{underlying "*-ŋ-"} for inanimate nouns.
    = render 'noun_endings', :animate => "-èm, -m", :animate_comments => "(-em, -m)", :inanimate => "-ŋ", :inanimate_comments => "(-ŋ, -əŋ)"
    %p With animate nouns, the suffix #{underlying "*-èm-"} is used when the noun stem ends in a consonant, and #{underlying "*-m-"} when it ends in a vowel. This particular “è” is a weak neutral vowel, meaning it is unchanging, but does not affect the harmony of subsequent vowels in any way. CVCVC nouns will lose their second vowel before #{underlying "*-èm-"} if it is short, and indeterminate vowels will tend towards the front vowel /e/ (even if the suffix is just *-m-).
    %p The inanimate suffix *-ŋ- will never come in direct contact with a consonant-final stem. An epenthetic schwa is always inserted, even if the final consonant of the root normally could form a final cluster with /n/. CVCVC will never lose their second vowel in this situation.
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*meme", :eng => "mother", :ochets => "мемем", :translit => "memem", :breakdown => "meme-m", :underlying => "me{f}me{f+}-m" },
                { :stem => "*nas", :eng => "eye", :ochets => "насем", :translit => "nasem", :breakdown => "nas-em", :underlying => "na{b+}s-è{b}m" },
                { :stem => "*čib", :eng => "dog", :ochets => "чибем", :translit => "čibem", :breakdown => "čib-em", :underlying => "či{f+}b-è{b}m" },
                { :stem => "*ǧəl", :eng => "hand", :ochets => "ҕелем", :translit => "ǧelem", :breakdown => "ǧal-em", :underlying => "ǧə{f}l-è{f}m" },
                { :stem => "*sent", :eng => "heart", :ochets => "сентем", :translit => "sentem", :breakdown => "sent-em", :underlying => "se{f+}nt-è{f}m" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Animate", :forms => forms
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*xee", :eng => "night", :ochets => "хееҥ", :translit => "xeeŋ", :breakdown => "xee-ŋ", :underlying => "xee{f+}-ŋ" },
                { :stem => "*huun", :eng => "morning", :ochets => "һуунәҥ", :translit => "huunəŋ", :breakdown => "huun-əŋ", :underlying => "huu{b+}n-ŋ" },
                { :stem => "*iš", :eng => "meat", :ochets => "һишәҥ", :translit => "hišəŋ", :breakdown => "hiš-əŋ", :underlying => "i{f+}š-ŋ" },
                { :stem => "*čieǧl", :eng => "sled", :ochets => "чиеҕләҥ", :translit => "cieǧləŋ", :breakdown => "čieǧl-əŋ", :underlying => "čie{f+}ǧl-ŋ" },
                { :stem => "*laad", :eng => "city", :ochets => "лаадәҥ", :translit => "laadəŋ", :breakdown => "laad-əŋ", :underlying => "laa{b+}d-ŋ" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Inanimate", :forms => forms
    %p It is, however, not unusual to hear the animate ending -m- generalized to all nouns, presumably to help avoid confusion with the common plural suffix -ŋ.

  = section "Ablative Case" do
    %p The ablative case’s primary function is to mark the origin of an action. For animate nouns the suffix is -dats or -ats, and for inanimate nouns it is -čis, -iis, or -ič. These endings do not display any sort of vowel harmony, and are considered strong neutral vowels.
    = render 'noun_endings', :animate => "-dats, -ats", :inanimate => "-čis, -iis, -ič"
    %p The rules for which endings to use are more complicated for the ablative than for any other case.
    %p For animate nouns, -dats is used when the stem ends in a vowel or diphthong:
    %ul
      %li #{t "қаи", "qai"} ‘falcon’ → #{t "қаидац", "qaidats"} ‘from a falcon’
      %li #{t "баба", "baba"} ‘father’ → #{t "бабадац", "babadats"} ‘from father’
      %li #{t "коса", "kosa"} ‘cat’ → #{t "косадац", "kosadats"} ‘from a cat’
    %p And -ats is used when it ends in a consonant; however, -ats also causes the preceding consonant to be geminated, <em>unless</em> that consonant is preceded by another consonant or a schwa.
    %ul
      %li #{t "чаит", "čait"} ‘person’ → #{t "чаиттац", "čaittats"} ‘from a person’
      %li #{t "һух", "hux"} ‘horse’ → #{t "һуххац", "huxxats"} ‘from a horse’
      %li #{t "сесәл", "sesəl"} ‘reindeer’ → #{t "сеслац", "seslats"} ‘from a reindeer’
    %p All indeterminate vowels are realized as /a/, and no vowels are dropped in CVCVC stems.
    %p With inanimate nouns, the rules become even more involved. The ending -čis is used after polysyllabic stems ending in a vowel, after monosyllabic stems ending in a long high vowel, after any stem ending in a diphthong, and in all recent loanwords, regardless of the final sound of the stem. If added after a consonant, an epenthetic schwa is always inserted: -əčis; sandhi never takes place here.
    %ul
      %li #{t "нииге", "niige"} ‘book’ → #{t "ниигечис", "niigečis"} ‘from a book’
      %li #{t "һии", "hii"} ‘paper’ → #{t "һиичис", "hiičis"} ‘from paper’
      %li #{t "һеи", "hei"} ‘island’ → #{t "һеичис", "heičis"} ‘from an island’
      %li #{t "вооз", "wooz"} ‘car’ → #{t "воозәчис", "woozəčis"} ‘from a car’
    %p The ending -iis is used after all native stems ending in a consonant (meaning the form was incorporated before roughly the 14th century AD), so long as the vowel in the syllable immediately preceding the case ending is short.
    %ul
      %li #{t "чен", "čen"} ‘silver’ → #{t "чениис", "čeniis"} ‘from silver’
      %li #{t "деш", "deš"} ‘river’ → #{t "дешиис", "dešiis"} ‘from a river’
    %p The ending -ič is used with stems ending in a consonant in which the vowel immediately preceding the ending is long or a diphthong; and after roots ending in /aː eː oː/, which then shorten to /a e o/. It causes gemination of the preceding consonant.
    %ul
      %li #{t "коин", "koin"} ‘time’ → #{t "коинич", "koinič"} ‘from a time’
      %li #{t "чее", "čee"} ‘stone’ → #{t "чеич", "čeič"} ‘from stone’
      %li #{t "квоо", "kwoo"} ‘ice’ → #{t "квоич", "kwoič"} ‘from ice’
    %p As with animate nouns, CVCVC stems never lose any vowels, but unlike animate nouns, all indeterminate vowels are realized as /e/.<sup>1</sup>
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*meme", :eng => "mother", :ochets => "мемедац", :translit => "memedats", :breakdown => "meme-dats", :underlying => "me{f}me{f+}-da{b+}ts" },
                { :stem => "*nas", :eng => "eye", :ochets => "нассац", :translit => "nassats", :breakdown => "nas-sats", :underlying => "na{b+}s-da{b+}ts" },
                { :stem => "*čib", :eng => "dog", :ochets => "чиббац", :translit => "čibbats", :breakdown => "čib-bats", :underlying => "či{f+}b-da{b+}ts" },
                { :stem => "*ǧəl", :eng => "hand", :ochets => "ҕалац", :translit => "ǧalats", :breakdown => "ǧal-ats", :underlying => "ǧə{b}l-da{b+}ts" },
                { :stem => "*sent", :eng => "heart", :ochets => "сентац", :translit => "sentats", :breakdown => "sent-ats", :underlying => "se{f+}nt-da{b+}ts" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Animate", :forms => forms
    - forms = [ { :stem => "*xee", :eng => "night", :ochets => "хеич", :translit => "xeič", :breakdown => "xe-ič", :underlying => "xee{f+}-či{f+}s" },
                { :stem => "*huun", :eng => "morning", :ochets => "һууннич", :translit => "huunnič", :breakdown => "huun-nič", :underlying => "huu{b+}n-či{f+}s" },
                { :stem => "*iš", :eng => "meat", :ochets => "һишиис", :translit => "hišiis", :breakdown => "hiš-iis", :underlying => "i{f+}š-či{f+}s" },
                { :stem => "*čieǧl", :eng => "sled", :ochets => "чиеҕлич", :translit => "cieǧlič", :breakdown => "čieǧl-ič", :underlying => "čie{f+}ǧl-či{f+}s" },
                { :stem => "*laad", :eng => "city", :ochets => "лаадәчис", :translit => "laadəčis", :breakdown => "laad-əčis", :underlying => "laa{b+}d-či{f+}s" } ]
    = render 'noun_declension', :title => "Inanimate", :forms => forms
    %p Note that the rule stating the suffix -čis must be used with loanwords only applies when the ablative suffix is in direct contact with a morpheme of foreign origin. If a derivational or inflectional suffix of native origin is inserted between the foreign root and the ablative case ending, the endings -iis or -ič will be used instead: #{t "лаадәчис", "laadəčis"} “city (#{abbrev 'abl'})” → #{t "лааданииши", "laadaniiši"} “cities (#{abbrev 'abl'})” (underlyingly #{underlying "laa{b+}d-n-či{f+}s-I{f}"}).

= section "Number" do
  %p Očets has two numbers, a singular and plural. Nouns are by default singular, becoming plural through the use of suffixes. There are three main plural declension patterns: one for animate nouns, one for inanimate ones, and an anomalous class of former duals.

  = section "Animate Declension" do
    %p Most animate nouns form their plurals using the suffix -ŋ-, which immediately follows the noun stem and precedes any case endings. However, if the noun stem ends in /ŋ/ or /n/ (or in a cluster containing /ŋ/ or /n/), the suffix will change to -n-.
    %p If the noun stem ends in a vowel or diphthong, using either of these suffixes poses no problem. However, if the stem ends in -a, -e, -o, or -ö, an additional -i- is inserted in between it and the plural ending to form a diphthong /ai ei oi øi/; if the former vowel is long, it is shortened first.
    %ul
      %li #{t "коса", "kosa"} ‘cat’ → #{t "косаиҥ", "kosaiŋ"} ‘cats’
      %li #{t "һежди", "heždi"} ‘sable’ → #{t "һеждиҥ", "heždiŋ"} ‘sables’
      %li #{t "меи", "mei"} ‘fruit’ → #{t "меиҥ", "meiŋ"} ‘fruits’
    %p If the noun stem ends in a consonant, the stem is elongated with a final vowel; this form is known as the “full stem”. Unfortunately, the quality of this vowel is unpredictable, although the follow patterns apply:
    %ul
      %li The additional vowel is always short.
      %li For native stems, it is usually a full vowel (i.e., not a schwa), though not always. For foreign stems newer than about 800 years old, it is usually a schwa.
      %li If a full vowel, it always matches the harmony of the main root.
    %p Examples:
    %ul
      %li #{t "коим", "koim"} ‘wife’ → #{t "коимоҥ", "koimoŋ"} ‘wives’
      %li #{t "иуул", "iuul"} ‘friend’ → #{t "иууләҥ", "iuuləŋ"} ‘friends’
      %li #{t "қаал", "qaal"} ‘grandson’ → #{t "қаалаҥ", "qaalaŋ"} ‘grandsons’
    %p For native stems, these vowels are generally believed to have come from an original final vowel in Proto-Ob-Yeniseian which was later lost. The same is true of foreign stems that take a full vowel. Schwas are generally simply epenthetic consonants for stems that have always ended in a consonant.
    %p Adding the plural ending to monosyllabic nouns of the form (C)VC (containing a short vowel) will often cause the vowel to lengthen, and sometimes to undergo ablaut as well: /i/ → /eː/, /e/ → /aː/, and /u/ → /oː/. Lengthening is common with all such nouns, no matter their age, while ablaut only occurs on native stems.
    %ul
      %li #{t "вал", "wal"} ‘son’ → #{t "ваалыҥ", "waalyŋ"} ‘sons’
      %li #{t "қан", "qan"} ‘king’ → #{t "қаанән", "qaanən"} ‘kings’
      %li #{t "һим", "him"} ‘nut’ → #{t "һеемүҥ", "heemüŋ"} ‘nuts’
    %p Finally, two sorts of final consonants are prone to causing other irregularities: final velar stops /k g/ and final /s/.
    %p Final /k g/ stems fall into two subclasses. Older native stems usually lose these consonants, and then add the plural suffix -ŋ- directly to this contracted stem. Newer stems instead geminate the velar consonant, add a short echo vowel matching the quality of the vowel in the syllable immediately preceding, and then add -ŋ.
    %ul
      %li #{t "хаак", "xaak"} ‘man’ → #{t "хааҥ", "xaaŋ"} ‘men’
      %li #{t "квоск", "kwosk"} ‘pike (fish)’ → #{t "квосәҥ", "kwosəŋ"} ‘pikes’
      %li #{t "хундук", "xunduk"} ‘hazelnut’ → #{t "хундуккуҥ", "xundukkuŋ"} ‘hazelnuts’
    %p Native stems ending in /s/ similarly drop the /s/, and then add the plural ending directly to the contracted root. However, in such cases, the suffix is always -n, never -ŋ. Newer stems ending in /s/ behave regularly.
    %ul
      %li #{t "һаас", "haas"} ‘god’ → #{t "һаан", "haan"} ‘gods’
      %li #{t "тыыс", "tyys"} ‘brother’ → #{t "тыын", "tyyn"} ‘brothers’
      %li #{t "лаупс", "laups"} ‘fox’ → #{t "лаупсәҥ", "laupsəŋ"} ‘foxes’
    %p CVCVC nouns are stable, never losing any vowels.
    %p Stems ending in a cluster are more complex, with their realization frequently dependent on case endings. If the plural marker is followed by nothing or a suffix beginning with a consonant, the stem remains intact (i.e., CVCC-Vŋ-CV); if it is followed by a suffix beginning with a vowel, then a schwa is inserted into the cluster and the plural suffix vowel is lost (i.e., CVCC-Vŋ-V → CVCəC-ŋ-V). Indeterminate vowels are unfortunately completely unpredictable.
    %ul
      %li #{t "сент", "sent"} “heart (#{abbrev 'nom'})” → #{t "сентен", "senten"} “hearts (#{abbrev 'nom'})”
      %li #{t "сенте", "sente"} “heart (#{abbrev 'obj'})” → #{t "сенәнне", "senənne"} “hearts (#{abbrev 'obj'})”
      %li #{t "техәл", "texəl"} “otter (#{abbrev 'nom'})” → #{t "техлеҥ", "texleŋ"} “otters (#{abbrev 'nom'})”
      %li #{t "техле", "texle"} “otter (#{abbrev 'obj'})” → #{t "техәлҥе", "texəlŋe"} “otters (#{abbrev 'obj'})”
    %p Assimilation occurs between the plural suffix and all case endings as expected.
