    = section "Case Ending Irregularities" do
      %p When a plural suffix is present, the case-marking morphemes are for the most part identical to the ones used for singular nouns. However, there are a few exceptions.
      %p The expected objective ending for i-case plurals is **-s, giving a combined ending of **-ii-s/-yy-s. However, it is actually -Ø, meaning that the nominative plural and objective plural are identical. Note the following examples, instead of expected <i>**liemiis</i>, <i>**qamyys</i>, <i>**kabyys</i>.
      %ul
        %li
          #{t "лиеме", "lieme"} ‘table (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'obj'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "лиемии", "liemii"} ‘tables (#{abbrev 'obj'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "lie{f+}m-è{f+}"} → #{underlying "lie{f+}m-II{f}-Ø"})
        %li
          #{t "қаме", "qame"} ‘arrow (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'obj'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "қамыы", "qamyy"} ‘arrows (#{abbrev 'obj'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "qa{b+}m-è{f+}"} → #{underlying "qa{b+}m-II{b}-Ø"})
        %li
          #{t "кабе", "kabe"} ‘spine (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'obj'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "кабыы", "kabyy"} ‘spines (#{abbrev 'obj'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "ka{b+}b-è{f+}"} → #{underlying "ka{b+}b-II{b}-Ø"})
      %p The plural ending and case ending merge in the  genitive plural as *-ndÌ-. In the n-class plurals, this is not especially apparent. This ending has spread analogically to t- and i-class nouns, leading to what appears to be a double marking of plurality.
      %ul
        %li
          #{t "саалчәд", "saalčəd"} ‘sea (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'gen'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "саалчынды", "saalčyndy"} ‘seas (#{abbrev 'gen'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "saa{b+}lč-dI{b→0}"} → #{underlying "saa{b+}lč-ndÌ{b}"})
        %li
          #{t "чиѕи", "čidzi"} ‘root (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'gen'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "чицаүтәнды", "čitsaütəndy"} ‘roots (#{abbrev 'gen'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "či{f+}ts-dI{f}"} → #{underlying "či{f+}ts-aU{f→b+}t-ndÌ{b}"})
        %li
          #{t "қанды", "qandy"} ‘arrow (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'gen'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "қамыынды", "qamyyndy"} ‘arrows (#{abbrev 'gen'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "qa{b+}m-dI{b}"} → #{underlying "qa{b+}m-II{b}-ndÌ{b}"})
      %p If the epenthetic vowel of an n-class noun is non-schwa, it stays in the lative and translative cases, even though the actual plural marker -n- disappears. This is also true of the ablative, except in this case the -n- remains (see next comment). For instance, the epenthetic vowel of #{t "саалч", "saalč"} ‘sea’ is -y-, seen in the nominative plural #{t "саалчын", "saalčyn"}.
      %ul
        %li
          #{t "саалче", "saalče"} ‘sea (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'obj'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "саалчыне", "saalčyne"} ‘seas (#{abbrev 'obj'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "saa{b+}lč-è{f+}"} → #{underlying "saa{b+}lč-n-è{f+}"})
        %li
          #{t "саалчола", "saalčola"} ‘sea (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'lat'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "саалчылаи", "saalčylai"} ‘seas (#{abbrev 'lat'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "saa{b+}lč-o{b+}la{b}"} → #{underlying "saa{b+}lč-la{b}-I{b}"})
        %li
          #{t "саалчәҥ", "saalčəŋ"} ‘sea (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'tra'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "саалчыҥы", "saalčyŋy"} ‘seas (#{abbrev 'tra'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "saa{b+}lč-ŋ"} → #{underlying "saa{b+}lč-ŋ-I{b}"})
        %li
          #{t "саалчич", "saalčič"} ‘sea (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'abl'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "саалчынииши", "saalčyniiši"} ‘seas (#{abbrev 'abl'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "saa{b+}lč-či{f+}s"} → #{underlying "saa{b+}lč-n-či{f+}s-I{f}"})
      %p The ablative case marker has three possible surface realizations in the singular: -čis, -iis, and -ič. In the plural, however, there are only two: -ič-i (with gemination of the preceding consonant if not in a cluster) and -iiš-i (with no gemination); the former is used whenever the previous syllable contains a long vowel or diphthong, and the latter when it contains a short vowel:
      %ul
        %li
          #{t "һоотич", "hootič"} ‘bone (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'abl'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "һоотичи", "hootiči"} ‘bones (#{abbrev 'abl'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "oo{b+}t-či{f+}s"} → #{underlying "oo{b+}t-či{f+}s-I{f}"})
        %li
          #{t "қамиис", "qamiis"} ‘arrow (#{underlying "#{abbrev 'abl'})’"} → #{underlying "#{t "қамииши", "qamiiši"} ‘arrows (#{abbrev 'abl'}"})’
          %br
          (#{underlying "qa{b+}m-či{f+}s"} → #{underlying "qa{b+}m-či{f+}s-I{f}"})
      %p However, n-class nouns will reinsert the plural ending -n- if the stem ends in a vowel, before the ablative ending (including when the epenthetic stem-extending vowel is present, as mentioned in the previous note). This -n- will never undergo gemination.
      %ul
        %li
