= section "Prenominal Affixes" do
  %p “Prenominal affixes” refers to a disparate group of prefixes that share in common the fact that they are attached to the very beginning of an Očets noun, before even the definite or possessive prefixes. In modern Očets only four prenominals are still in use, two of which are of obvious Slavic origin and one which is disputable.
  %p Prenominals in Ob languages are usually divided into two subclasses: derivational<sup>6</sup> and non-derivational<sup>7</sup>.
  %p Derivational prenominals serve no grammatical function, but rather modify the meaning of the noun to create a new word entirely. They differ from other forms of derivational morphology only in the fact that they are not contiguous with the actual noun stem. While the other Ob languages that are reasonably well-attested seem to have a rich system of such prenominals, Očets only has one, the collective hO-. It is used most commonly with nationalities, and always in conjunction with the definite article, which will typically appear in its vowelless form and undergo assimilation.
  %table.noundecl
    %tr
      %th Prefix
      %th Meaning
    %tr
      %td ho-/hö-
      %td collective
  %table.noundecl
    %tr
      %th Base
      %th With Prenominal
      %th Underlying
    %tr
      %td
        = t("бикчит", "bikčit", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “(a) Novegradian”
      %td
        = t("һөббикчисе", "höbbikčise", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “the Novegradians”
      %td= underlying("hO{f}-tV{0}-bi{f}kči{b+}t-A{f}")
    %tr
      %td
        = t("лууск", "luusk", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “(a) Russian”
      %td
        = t("һоллууска", "holluuska", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “the Russians”
      %td= underlying("hO{b}-tV{0}-luu{b+}sk-A{b}")
    %tr
      %td
        = t("паранцуус", "parantsuus", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “Frenchman”
      %td
        = t("һотпаранцууса", "hotparantsuusa", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “the French”
      %td= underlying("hO{b}-tV{0}-pa{b}ra{b}ntsuu{b+}s-A{b}")
    %tr
      %td
        = t("һеҕлии", "heǧlii", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “Englishman”
      %td
        = t("һөсеҕлии", "höseǧlii", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “the English”
      %td= underlying("hO{f}-t-he{f}ǧlii{f+}-A{b→0}")
  %p It can also have an associative plural function, meaning “those people collectively associated with X”. When used with a name as a base (especially surnames), it refers to a family<sup>8</sup>.
  %table.noundecl
    %tr
      %th Base
      %th With Prenominal
      %th Underlying
    %tr
      %td
        = t("cкоола", "skoola", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “school”
      %td
        = t("һотәскоолаа", "hotəskoolaa", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “school students”
      %td= underlying("hO{b}-tV{0}-skoo{b}la{b+}-A{b}")
    %tr
      %td
        = t("Иванеу", "Iwáneu", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “Iváneu (surname)”
      %td
        = t("һөсиваневе", "hösiwanewe", :linebreak => true)
        %br
        “the Iváneu family”
      %td= underlying("hO{f}-t-I{f}vá{b}neu{f+}-A{f}")
  %p Non-derivational prenominals have a clear grammatical function, and are sometimes known as “minor cases” due to their somewhat case-like role. Očets has three such forms: the comitative, distributive,  and contrastive negative (or abessive).
  %table.nounendings
    %tr
      %th Prefix
      %th Meaning
    %tr
      %td sa-
      %td comitative
    %tr
      %td po-
      %td distributive
    %tr
      %td nyy-/nii-
      %td contrastive negative/abessive
  %p The distributive po- and contrastive negative nyy-/nii- are clearly loans from Novegradian or Russian #{t "по", "po"} and #{t "ни", "ni"}. The comitative sa- is of debatable origin, being either a loan from Novegradian со <i>so</i> “with”, or cognate to the suffix -sa seen in a number of Yeniseian languages. And while po- and nyy-/nii- may be used in conjunction with any case, sa- may only be used with the instrumental case.
  %p The use of these prefixes will be discussed later.

= section "Predicate Agreement Suffixes" do
  %p The predicate agreement suffixes are a series of markers that must be placed on the complement of the verb “to be”, whether it be noun, postpositional phrase, adjective, or pronoun. It agrees with the subject of the sentence in person and number, as well as animacy in the third person. There is also an impersonal form for sentences without a grammatical subject. They always appear in the final slot.
  %table.noundecl
    %tr
      %th
      %th Singular
      %th Plural
    %tr
      %th 1st
      %td
        = underlying("*-Àš")
        %br
        (-aš, -eš)
      %td
        = underlying("*-šÌŋ")
        %br
        (-šiŋ, -šyŋ)
    %tr
      %th 2nd
      %td
        = underlying("*-Àk")
        %br
        (-ak, -ek)
      %td
        = underlying("*-kÙŋ")
        %br
        (-kuŋ, -küŋ)
    %tr
      %th 3rd (A)
      %td
        = underlying("*-Àd")
        %br
        (-ad, -ed)
      %td
        = underlying("*-Àn")
        %br
        (-an, -en)
    %tr
      %th 3rd (I)
      %td{:colspan => 2}
        = underlying("*-dÌ")
        %br
        (-di, -dy)
    %tr
      %th Impersonal
      %td{:colspan => 2}
        = underlying("*-Àm")
        %br
        (-am, -em)
  %p The following forms of #{t "һочец", "hočets"} can thus be interpreted as complete sentences:
  %p
    #{t "Һочецеш", "Hočetseš"} “I am Očets”
    %br
    #{t "Һочецек", "Hočetsek"} “You are Očets”
    %br
    #{t "Һочецед", "Hočetsed"} “He/She is Očets”
    %br
    #{t "Һочеѕи", "Hočedzi"} “It is Očets”
    %br
    #{t "Һочецеҥешиҥ", "Hočetseŋešiŋ"} “We are Očets”
    %br
    #{t "Һочецеҥекүҥ", "Hočetseŋeküŋ"} “You all are Očets”
    %br
    #{t "Һочецеҥеен", "Hočetseŋeen"} “They are Očets”
    %br
    #{t "Һочецеҥеди", "Hočetseŋedi"} “Those are Očets”
    %br
    #{t "Һочецем", "Hočetsem"} “One is Očets”

= section "Relative Suffix" do
  %p The primary function of the relative suffix *-d- is to relativize a postpositional or otherwise oblique phrase, thereby allowing it to directly modify a noun almost like an adjective would (e.g., #{t "туҕвуулд тахаака", "tuǧwuuld taxaaka"} “the man [that is] in the house” from #{underlying "*tV{b}-ǧuu{b+}-I{b→0}l-d tV{b}-xaa{b+}k-A{b}"}). It is inserted after any case/number suffixes, and suppresses the indirective suffix even if the word is definite. Once again, its usage will be discussed at a later point.
  %p One irregular behavior of this suffix, however, is that it is required on postpositional/oblique phrases serving as the complement of the verb “to be”. Here it will be forced to take a predicate agreement suffix, which comes at the very end of the noun and will result in the indirective marker reappearing if it was suppressed by the relative suffix, though only if the predicate agreement suffix begins with a consonant. For example:
  = example_sentence :ochets => "Cуулҥа туҕвуулдан.",
                     :translit => "Suulŋa tuǧwuuldan.",
                     :breakdown => "S-uul-ŋ-a tu-ǧwuu-l-d-an.",
                     :underlying => "*t-iuu{b+}l-ŋ-A{b} tV{b}-ǧuu{b+}-I{b→0}l-d-À{b}n",
                     :gloss => "#{abbrev 'def'}-friend-#{abbrev 'anim.pl'}-#{abbrev 'ind'} #{abbrev 'def'}-house-#{abbrev 'loc'}-#{abbrev 'rel'}-#{abbrev '3pl.anim.pred'}",
                     :eng => "The friends are in the house",
                     :comment => "(no indirective on “house”)"
  = example_sentence :ochets => "Cиниигене туҕвуулдады.",
                     :translit => "Siniigene tuǧwuuldady.",
                     :breakdown => "Si-niige-n-e tu-ǧwuu-l-d-a-dy.",
                     :underlying => "*tV{f}-nii{f}ge{f+}-n-À{f} tV{b}-ǧuu{b+}-I{b→0}l-d-À{b}-dÌ{b}",
                     :gloss => "#{abbrev 'def'}-book-#{abbrev 'inan.pl'}-#{abbrev 'ind'} #{abbrev 'def'}-house-#{abbrev 'loc'}-#{abbrev 'rel'}-#{abbrev 'ind'}-#{abbrev '3.inan.pred'}",
                     :eng => "The books are in the house",
                     :comment => "(with indirective on “house”)"

= section "Foreign Loans" do
  %p Foreign loans that have not been fully nativized (e.g., they still contain foreign clusters, mix front and back vowels, or simply still feel foreign) still have access to most Očets nominal morphology, although their declension is dramatically simplified. In general, they do not undergo any sort of alteration of the root itself, although sandhi still takes place amongst the native affixes (e.g., #{t "туниверсидатла", "tuniwersidatla"} “to the university” rather than <i>**tuniwersidalla</i>). They also form their plurals quite regularly, using *-(ə)n-.
  %p The harmony pattern of a loan word is typically determined by the final vowel of the stem. However, even front-vowel suffixes that normally trigger palatalization will not affect the stem.
  %p Only in one area is the declension of foreign loans truly defective: they are unable to take first- and second-person possessive markers, instead relying on special possessive pronouns. While the third-person and impersonal possessive suffixes are still used, they will often be accompanied by a pronoun as well, resulting in double-marking of the possessor.

= section "Enclitic Coordinators" do
  %p Nouns and pronouns may appear with one of four enclitic coordinators, discourse particles that attach themselves to the end of a noun to relate its role to a participant in a previous sentence or clause. These are known as the “positive equative” ([X] and Y as well), the “negative equative” ([not X] nor Y), the “positive contrastive” ([not X] but Y), and the “negative contrastive” ([X] but not Y). The full usage of these will be explained at a later time. These enclitics may be used with nouns or pronouns in any case.
  %table.noundecl
    %tr
      %th
      %th Positive
      %th Negative
    %tr
      %th Equative
      %td
        = underlying("*-kAi")
        %br
        (-kai, -čei)
      %td
        = underlying("*-fa")
        %br
        (-fa, -fe)
    %tr
      %th Contrastive
      %td
        = underlying("*-qA(?)")
        %br
        (-ǧe, -qa)
      %td
        = underlying("*-sury")
        %br
        (-sury)
  %p The positive forms show harmony agreement, while the negative forms lack it entirely. However, the front vowel form of the positive contrastive #{underlying "*-qA"} is -ǧe, not the expected **qa (← *qe).
  %p These clitics are added as-is to a word ending in a vowel; if the word ends in a consonant, an epenthetic schwa is always inserted. Compare #{t "шииуулакаи", "šiiuulakai"} “my friend as well” and #{t "иуулəкаи", "iuuləkai"} “a friend as well”.

%p &nbsp;

%hr.footnote

%p 1) This very complex behavior has to do with the fact that in origin, the Očets ablative case is both a compound case built upon an older case (i.e., the genitive), and was at one time phrasal. It is believed to have come from pre-Proto-Ob *qaut-Vs, the instrumental form of *qaut- “way, path, road”, which was preceded by a noun in the genitive case with the sense “by way of X”. In Proto-Ob, the ablative suffix was something like *da-t-as (← *da-qt-as) for animate nouns and *tsi-s-es (← *di-qt-es) for inanimate nouns, with the different vowel patterns emerging from the two different inherited forms of the genitive suffix.
%p 2) The older forms, before this levelling occurred, were presumably *lookəny and *kiisəŋi. These are not attested in any Očets dialects or the few surviving examples of Old Očets, but they are seen in other Ob languages.
%p 3) The stem *den- always calls for back vowel harmony.
%p 4) Etymologically, these two forms are actually related, coming from the Proto-Ob-Yeniseian root *tūx- “clay, earth” and its plural *tūx-Vn’.
%p 5) The loss of the indirective suffix after a numeral in the examples below will be explained later.
%p 6) Sometimes also known as “persistent”.
%p 7) Sometimes also known as “non-persistant” or as “minor cases”.
%p 8) This is the reason why many Novegradianized Očets surnames begin with /o/. For instance, the surname #{t "Отазатоу", "Otázatou"} derives from Očets #{t "һотазата", "hotazata"} “descendents/clan of Azat”.

